All right, I think I
might come around here.

00:00:38.780 --> 00:00:42.990
How many of you guys have ever
had like a goal or a dream

00:00:42.990 --> 00:00:45.140
or something you really
wanted to have happen,

00:00:45.140 --> 00:00:47.234
but you couldn't figure
out how to make it happen?

00:00:47.234 --> 00:00:48.650
You've had that
experience, right?

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:49.910
You probably have certain
things in your life

00:00:49.910 --> 00:00:50.480
like that right now.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:52.240
I thought a good way
for me to get started

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:54.260
to talk a little
bit about this book

00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:56.070
and what I'm going to
talk about here today

00:00:56.070 --> 00:00:57.760
is actually tell a
little bit of my story.

00:00:57.760 --> 00:00:59.968
Some of you may know that,
some of you on live stream

00:00:59.968 --> 00:01:03.637
may know that as well, but also
sort of as it relates to some

00:01:03.637 --> 00:01:04.970
of the core themes of this book.

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:07.630
But it's actually story related
to the first book that I wrote,

00:01:07.630 --> 00:01:10.690
which is called "Focus
on the Good Stuff."

00:01:10.690 --> 00:01:13.870
So as some of you know, my
background-- I grew up here

00:01:13.870 --> 00:01:16.600
in the Bay Area, I played
baseball most of my life.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:19.380
I actually got drafted right out
of high school by the Yankees.

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:20.720
Didn't end up signing
with the Yankees

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:23.136
because I got an opportunity
to play baseball at Stanford.

00:01:23.136 --> 00:01:25.395
So I go to Stanford,
play there, then I

00:01:25.395 --> 00:01:28.510
get drafted out of Stanford
by the Kansas City Royals,

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:29.590
signed a pro contract.

00:01:29.590 --> 00:01:32.215
The way it works in professional
baseball here in the US,

00:01:32.215 --> 00:01:34.180
some of you know, you sign a
pro contract with a major league

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:36.470
team, you still have to
go in the minor leagues.

00:01:36.470 --> 00:01:38.149
I ended up injuring
my pitching arm

00:01:38.149 --> 00:01:40.190
when I was in the minor
leagues with Kansas City,

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:43.500
so my career ended a lot
sooner than I wanted it to.

00:01:43.500 --> 00:01:46.140
So that was an interesting
challenge that I went through.

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:48.962
But as I was kind of making it
my way through that process--

00:01:48.962 --> 00:01:50.420
I had to get a job,
figure out what

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:51.740
I was going to do with the
rest of my life, right?

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:52.615
It was the late '90s.

00:01:52.615 --> 00:01:54.960
I got a job working for
an internet company,

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:56.907
actually, not that
far from where

00:01:56.907 --> 00:01:57.990
we're standing right here.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:00.180
I worked for 24/7 Media.

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:02.750
Our biggest competitor was
DoubleClick at the time.

00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:04.362
So I was in online
ad sales, actually.

00:02:04.362 --> 00:02:06.070
Worked there for about
a year and a half.

00:02:06.070 --> 00:02:08.520
Then I went to go get a job
at a sports website called

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:12.020
rivals.com, and it was
kind of a new startup

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:13.150
and a lot of VC backing.

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:15.790
We were all going to get rich,
it was going to go public.

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:18.940
And then the dot.com bubble
burst and I lost my job.

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:20.610
But I had this
idea-- and this had

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:23.604
been for a number of years--
that I really wanted to speak

00:02:23.604 --> 00:02:25.020
and I wanted to
write and I wanted

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:26.320
to try to inspire people.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:27.820
I didn't really
know how to do that,

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:29.710
but I got some encouragement
and I got some coaching,

00:02:29.710 --> 00:02:31.510
and I decided at the
beginning of 2001,

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:34.230
even though I was nervous,
to start my own business

00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:35.330
as a coach, as a speaker.

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:37.080
And one of the things
that I wanted to do,

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:38.690
and one of things I
figured you have to do

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:39.510
is write a book, right?

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:40.940
I mean, that's part
of how you do that.

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:42.340
So I decided I
wanted write a book.

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:44.270
And I didn't know anything
about writing a book,

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:45.880
but I started reading books
about how to write a book,

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:48.004
and I started meeting people
about how you do that.

00:02:48.004 --> 00:02:50.390
And within not that long,
maybe about nine months,

00:02:50.390 --> 00:02:52.407
a year, I had met a
guy who was helping me

00:02:52.407 --> 00:02:54.240
and kind of coaching
me and putting together

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:55.330
a book proposal.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:57.230
Because that's sort of what you
have to do to then get an agent

00:02:57.230 --> 00:02:59.040
and then get a book deal, and I
was learning all these things.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:00.123
OK, so I start to do this.

00:03:00.123 --> 00:03:01.920
So then fast
forward, it literally

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:04.860
goes over the span
of about five years.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:07.040
I go through two
literary agents.

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:11.890
I get rejected 25 times by
every publisher on the planet.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:12.790
And I'm frustrated.

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:15.490
And now it's like
early 2006, I'm

00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:17.220
on my second literary agent.

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:19.910
We've gone through all
these series of rejections.

00:03:19.910 --> 00:03:20.879
And I'm frustrated.

00:03:20.879 --> 00:03:22.920
And I've been speaking
now for a number of years,

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:24.836
and I've been working
with some cool companies

00:03:24.836 --> 00:03:27.010
here in the Bay Area
and around the country.

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:29.440
And my agent says
to me, listen, Mike.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:30.459
You're a nice guy.

00:03:30.459 --> 00:03:33.000
I know you're really passionate
about this whole appreciation

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:33.980
thing.

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:36.680
But you know what, I don't
think it's going to work.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.890
Maybe you gotta change the
topic, or I don't know,

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:40.340
but the publishers
aren't into it.

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:42.160
And I listened to
her on the phone.

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:43.549
This is like late
February, 2006.

00:03:43.549 --> 00:03:45.840
My wife, Michelle, and I--
we live in the Bay Area now.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:46.687
We live up in Marin.

00:03:46.687 --> 00:03:48.020
We've lived here our whole life.

00:03:48.020 --> 00:03:49.030
She's from here as well.

00:03:49.030 --> 00:03:51.140
We had just had our
first daughter, Samantha,

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:53.097
who was a new baby,
who's now eight.

00:03:53.097 --> 00:03:54.430
But Samantha had just been born.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:56.721
So I have this conversation
with my agent on the phone,

00:03:56.721 --> 00:03:59.210
and I listen to her feedback,
and I go to sleep that night.

00:03:59.210 --> 00:04:00.740
But I'm pissed.

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:02.430
Like, I can't even sleep.

00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:05.012
And I'm not necessarily mad at
her, I'm just mad in general.

00:04:05.012 --> 00:04:06.720
And I don't know what
the anger is about.

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:08.690
And I'm talking to my wife and
she's trying to go to sleep,

00:04:08.690 --> 00:04:09.760
and I can't sleep.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:11.270
And then finally in the
middle of the night it hit me,

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:11.870
and I went, you know what?

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:13.290
I realize what's going on.

00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:16.420
I keep waiting for permission.

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.910
I'm waiting for someone
to tell me I'm ready.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.600
I don't know if it's my agent or
some publisher or some someone.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:23.110
And I said, you know what?

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:24.350
I'm gonna write this book.

00:04:24.350 --> 00:04:25.400
So I called her
the next day and I

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:27.066
said, listen, I
appreciate the feedback,

00:04:27.066 --> 00:04:28.500
But I gotta tell you something.

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:30.167
I'm not waiting anymore.

00:04:30.167 --> 00:04:31.750
I've been waiting
for your permission,

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:33.060
I've been waiting-- I'm
just not waiting anymore.

00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:34.268
I'm going to write this book.

00:04:34.268 --> 00:04:35.900
I'll publish it
myself if I have to.

00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:37.650
That's what I'm going to do.

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:38.900
And she said, all right, Mike.

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:40.191
I understand you're frustrated.

00:04:40.191 --> 00:04:42.599
Listen, she said,
before you do that, I've

00:04:42.599 --> 00:04:44.890
got a couple other publishers
that I hadn't reached out

00:04:44.890 --> 00:04:45.890
to yet.

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:47.590
Let me send it out
to all three of them

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:49.365
and see what they think.

00:04:49.365 --> 00:04:50.990
She calls back two
days later and says,

00:04:50.990 --> 00:04:52.365
you're not going
to believe this.

00:04:52.365 --> 00:04:54.880
All three of them want it.

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:57.490
And I ended up publishing
my first book with Wiley.

00:04:57.490 --> 00:04:59.320
And what was interesting about
it, because I looked at it--

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:00.770
and I remember thinking to
myself even at the time,

00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:02.960
but especially now
looking back-- nothing

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:04.720
had changed with
my book proposal.

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:07.260
Quite frankly, I had literally
had the same proposal

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:08.230
for almost five years.

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:10.438
I mean, I had adjusted it
a little bit along the way.

00:05:10.438 --> 00:05:12.110
It was the same thing.

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:13.980
The only thing that
changed was me.

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:15.300
Something shifted inside of me.

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:16.250
I got mad.

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:17.390
I don't know, I just
had a new daughter,

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:18.850
I don't know what it was,
but something shifted.

00:05:18.850 --> 00:05:21.290
And now I can see, looking
back-- that was 2006,

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:23.930
I wrote the book, it came out
in '07-- I can see in hindsight

00:05:23.930 --> 00:05:25.790
now, looking back,
oh, you know what?

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:28.040
I wasn't actually ready
up until that moment.

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.550
And the moment I was ready,
that's when it happened.

00:05:30.550 --> 00:05:32.300
And you can probably
look in your own life

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:34.674
and see there's been a lot of
situations and circumstance

00:05:34.674 --> 00:05:36.030
that happened just like that.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:37.956
You can't always
tell in the moment.

00:05:37.956 --> 00:05:40.080
You connect the dots when
you look back and go, oh,

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:41.680
that's why that happened.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:44.820
So a lot of the focus of this
new book that I just wrote

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:45.550
is about that.

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:46.930
How do we shift internally?

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:49.570
What do we need to shift
and change internally

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:52.230
so that the world
around us changes?

00:05:52.230 --> 00:05:54.740
But in addition to that,
it's also really about

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:58.800
that one of the core themes of
this book is self-compassion.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:00.290
Self-compassion.

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:02.090
And I've been fascinated
by this and have

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:03.430
started to research
this a little bit.

00:06:03.430 --> 00:06:05.990
It's been something that I've
both struggled with and found

00:06:05.990 --> 00:06:08.870
interesting over the course of
most of my life and my work.

00:06:08.870 --> 00:06:10.630
And especially
when I find myself

00:06:10.630 --> 00:06:12.680
in environments
like here at Google

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:15.570
with a lot of really
smart, talented people,

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:18.010
I find that many of us
struggle with our relationship

00:06:18.010 --> 00:06:19.550
with ourselves.

00:06:19.550 --> 00:06:22.230
And how do we treat ourselves
with that sense of compassion?

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:23.980
So what I hope to do here
is to talk a little bit.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:26.110
I'm going to share a few stories
from the book and a few ideas

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:27.960
related to
self-compassion and how

00:06:27.960 --> 00:06:29.930
we can make some of
those internal shifts.

00:06:29.930 --> 00:06:31.270
But I also hope-- and even
though I know some of you

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:32.300
are watching this
video or you're

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:34.530
watching us on live stream-- for
those of you here in the room,

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:35.770
that we have a
bit of a dialogue,

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:36.980
that I'll be able to
answer some questions.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:38.771
But we'll talk about
this, how this relates

00:06:38.771 --> 00:06:41.830
to you and to your life, so that
you can take some things away

00:06:41.830 --> 00:06:43.530
that you can actually use.

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:44.710
Cool?

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:46.430
So take a moment right
now, if you would.

00:06:46.430 --> 00:06:47.430
and if you're watching us on
live stream you can do this.

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:48.480
If you're by
yourself, maybe just

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:50.050
jot it down or think about it.

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:51.080
If you're watching
the video, same thing.

00:06:51.080 --> 00:06:52.970
But for those of you here,
pair up with someone and talk

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:55.350
a little bit about for you,
thinking about--and I'll talk

00:06:55.350 --> 00:06:58.800
a little more about
self-compassion-- but for you,

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:02.020
in terms of your
relationship with yourself,

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:04.600
what do you find makes it
difficult or challenging

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:08.500
for you to be kind and
compassionate to yourself?

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.510
Because I know for many
of us, myself included,

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:11.850
that can be challenging.

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:13.430
So what kind of
things do you find

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:15.790
get in the way of
your own ability

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:17.757
to be kind and
compassionate to yourself?

00:07:17.757 --> 00:07:20.340
So pair up with someone and just
chat a little bit about that,

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:22.220
and then we'll dive into it.

