00:33:36.569 --> 00:33:38.110
So the mechanisms
for sort of dealing

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:42.750
with the guilt when I
take time for myself.

00:33:42.750 --> 00:33:43.770
That's a good question.

00:33:43.770 --> 00:33:47.250
I think-- I'm a talker by
nature, it's what I do, right?

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:48.790
So I think communicating
and talking

00:33:48.790 --> 00:33:50.220
is a really important thing.

00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:52.587
So acknowledging it
if I'm feeling guilty.

00:33:52.587 --> 00:33:54.670
And usually the places
where I tend to feel guilty

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:58.637
are with my wife and my girls,
because again, I'm on the road

00:33:58.637 --> 00:34:00.220
and that poses a
challenge in my life.

00:34:00.220 --> 00:34:02.750
I'm away from my family more
than I'd ultimately like to be.

00:34:02.750 --> 00:34:04.470
And then when on
top of it I say,

00:34:04.470 --> 00:34:07.250
hey babe, I really need to go
up Calistoga for a couple days,

00:34:07.250 --> 00:34:09.350
Napa, whatever.

00:34:09.350 --> 00:34:12.221
Sometimes some guilt and-- but
then we'll talk about that,

00:34:12.221 --> 00:34:13.679
and I'll say, I
feel really guilty.

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:15.260
And then we'll communicate,
and sometimes it's

00:34:15.260 --> 00:34:16.843
a negotiation a bit
about what's going

00:34:16.843 --> 00:34:19.150
to work, what's not going to
work, where the impact is.

00:34:19.150 --> 00:34:20.760
The other place where
I tend to feel guilty,

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:22.468
because relationships
and connections are

00:34:22.468 --> 00:34:24.580
so important to me-- but
as my life has gotten

00:34:24.580 --> 00:34:27.360
bigger and busier and I'm doing
more things both professionally

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:29.530
and then with my
family, I don't get

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:31.980
to connect with and see a
lot of my friends and people

00:34:31.980 --> 00:34:34.080
I care about a lot.

00:34:34.080 --> 00:34:35.219
So that poses a challenge.

00:34:35.219 --> 00:34:36.927
But again, to me it's
about communicating

00:34:36.927 --> 00:34:40.194
that, not like an excuse,
but just being real about it.

00:34:40.194 --> 00:34:42.110
Instead of pretending,
because for a long time

00:34:42.110 --> 00:34:43.960
I would do the thing
like, hey, yeah, great,

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:45.320
we should get
together, all right?

00:34:45.320 --> 00:34:47.030
You know, all that BS
stuff that but we do.

00:34:47.030 --> 00:34:48.370
Because really what I
was feeling is like,

00:34:48.370 --> 00:34:50.330
gosh, I don't know
how to manage my life

00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:52.745
and all my relationships
and connections.

00:34:52.745 --> 00:34:54.870
And now, look, again, with
all the great technology

00:34:54.870 --> 00:34:56.820
and all the way we're
now more interconnected,

00:34:56.820 --> 00:34:59.070
there's just more people in
my sphere than used to be,

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:01.250
and I'm sure that's
true for most of us.

00:35:01.250 --> 00:35:03.590
And then the question becomes
the level of authenticity

00:35:03.590 --> 00:35:07.490
and the real connection
of those relationships.

00:35:07.490 --> 00:35:09.580
So it's a challenge
to some degree,

00:35:09.580 --> 00:35:12.500
but I also think the more
real we are about it,

00:35:12.500 --> 00:35:14.310
people can understand.

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:16.450
And even again, talking
from that perspective

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:18.010
of-- sometimes
when I'm concerned,

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:19.180
if I'm going to do
something that might seem

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:21.920
selfish or self-absorbed or I'm
worried someone might judge me,

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:23.960
I will often just bring that up.

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:25.890
But not like a
critique, but more just

00:35:25.890 --> 00:35:27.700
like from that
vulnerable place of like,

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:30.274
here's what I really want
to do, but I'm afraid

00:35:30.274 --> 00:35:31.940
if I do that, you're
going to think this

00:35:31.940 --> 00:35:33.690
or it's going to be a
problem or whatever.

00:35:33.690 --> 00:35:35.600
So then we talk about it.

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:36.940
Does that make sense?

00:35:36.940 --> 00:35:38.691
And you know, I had
another mentor of mine

00:35:38.691 --> 00:35:40.648
say this great thing to
me a couple years back.

00:35:40.648 --> 00:35:42.880
He said, you know, Mike,
what stands between you

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:44.546
and the kind of
relationships you really

00:35:44.546 --> 00:35:45.770
want to have with people?

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:46.770
And I said, what's that?

00:35:46.770 --> 00:35:48.686
And he said, probably a
ten-minute sweaty palm

00:35:48.686 --> 00:35:50.831
conversation you're
too afraid to have.

00:35:50.831 --> 00:35:53.330
He said, you get really good
at those ten-minute sweaty palm

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:55.710
conversations, you'll have
fantastic relationships.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:58.440
He said, but if you avoid
them like most people do,

00:35:58.440 --> 00:35:59.615
things will be tricky.

00:35:59.615 --> 00:36:01.990
And you hope you roll the dice
and get really cool people

00:36:01.990 --> 00:36:03.448
to work with and
really cool people

00:36:03.448 --> 00:36:06.160
in your family, whatever, but
that's not usually the way

00:36:06.160 --> 00:36:08.010
it works out naturally.

00:36:08.010 --> 00:36:10.514
So that make sense?

