not like how it should be,

00:37:15.870 --> 00:37:17.870
because that's a judgment,
but how it is for me.

00:37:17.870 --> 00:37:19.740
Here's what I know
I really need.

00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:22.450
And then figuring out if what
I need and what works for me

00:37:22.450 --> 00:37:23.950
is going to work
in the environment.

00:37:23.950 --> 00:37:27.136
And sometimes the hard
reality is, it's not.

00:37:27.136 --> 00:37:29.200
It doesn't mean you're
bad or they're bad.

00:37:29.200 --> 00:37:31.890
It just means, wow,
I'm either going

00:37:31.890 --> 00:37:36.307
to have to inauthentically
abide by these norms-- and look,

00:37:36.307 --> 00:37:37.640
we do this all the time in life.

00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:39.250
So this doesn't make us
a terrible, weak person,

00:37:39.250 --> 00:37:40.120
like, I'm gonna do that.

00:37:40.120 --> 00:37:41.970
But be real about it with
ourselves first, and even

00:37:41.970 --> 00:37:42.650
with other people.

00:37:42.650 --> 00:37:45.066
But a lot of times there's
more wiggle room in negotiation

00:37:45.066 --> 00:37:46.479
than we think.

00:37:46.479 --> 00:37:48.270
One of my favorite
sayings is, the answer's

00:37:48.270 --> 00:37:50.580
always no if you don't ask.

00:37:50.580 --> 00:37:52.540
So we make assumptions
about stuff

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:53.710
that may or may not be true.

00:37:53.710 --> 00:37:54.793
So that's the first thing.

00:37:54.793 --> 00:37:56.570
The second thing
is-- I think it's

00:37:56.570 --> 00:37:57.850
really important-- boundaries.

00:37:57.850 --> 00:38:00.280
Having clear and clean
boundaries does not

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:01.960
mean that we're
righteous about them

00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:04.050
or they're etched in stone.

00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:07.961
But not having boundaries
creates problems down the road

00:38:07.961 --> 00:38:09.460
because people take
advantage of us,

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:12.084
people do things that don't work
for us, we don't say anything,

00:38:12.084 --> 00:38:14.380
and then we finally
do, we get pissed.

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:16.340
And then it's a problem
for them and for us.

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:17.020
And all of a sudden, whoa.

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:19.540
Think about conflicts that have
arisen at work about something

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:21.030
that you knew it was an
issue for a long time,

00:38:21.030 --> 00:38:22.230
you just didn't say anything.

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:23.410
And then you finally
said something

00:38:23.410 --> 00:38:25.500
and it has all this anger
and animosity behind it

00:38:25.500 --> 00:38:27.708
because you've been holding
onto it for three months.

00:38:27.708 --> 00:38:28.640
You know what I mean?

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:30.059
So it can be tricky.

00:38:30.059 --> 00:38:31.850
And at the end of the
day, you have a boss,

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:32.600
you have an employer.

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:33.980
There are rules,
there are norms,

00:38:33.980 --> 00:38:35.610
there are things that
we got to abide by.

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:38.193
If we're going to play that game
we gotta play by those rules.

00:38:38.193 --> 00:38:39.410
I played baseball, right?

00:38:39.410 --> 00:38:41.827
Even if I really felt like it,
you can't run to third base

00:38:41.827 --> 00:38:43.326
first, you have to
run to first base

00:38:43.326 --> 00:38:45.220
first because that's
the rules of that game.

00:38:45.220 --> 00:38:46.350
And I could argue
all I want, but it's

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:47.760
more comfortable for me to
go that way than this way,

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:49.720
and they'd say, sorry,
Mike, you're out.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:50.810
You don't get to play.

00:38:50.810 --> 00:38:52.710
So there is some
balance of that.

00:38:52.710 --> 00:38:55.080
And then the other thing is,
I think now more than ever,

00:38:55.080 --> 00:38:57.252
there's a lot of things
happening in our culture

00:38:57.252 --> 00:38:59.210
where we're finding--
there's a lot of research

00:38:59.210 --> 00:39:01.970
out there-- Arianna Huffington
just wrote a great book called

00:39:01.970 --> 00:39:04.594
"Thrive" that some of you may be
familiar with, where she talks

00:39:04.594 --> 00:39:06.870
specifically about the
importance of sleep-- it's

00:39:06.870 --> 00:39:09.030
probably the main
crux of that book,

00:39:09.030 --> 00:39:11.640
sleep, take care
yourself, meditate,

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:13.130
take care of your inner life.

00:39:13.130 --> 00:39:16.074
And she tells the story of
collapsing in her office

00:39:16.074 --> 00:39:18.490
and literally hitting her head
on the desk on the way down

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:20.740
as she was launching
the Huffington Post.

00:39:20.740 --> 00:39:22.949
And she ends up on the
floor in a pool of blood.

00:39:22.949 --> 00:39:24.990
And she says-- and I've
seen her speak about this

00:39:24.990 --> 00:39:25.800
and maybe some of
you have as well--

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:27.758
she goes, look, by every
conventional measure I

00:39:27.758 --> 00:39:29.340
was successful.

00:39:29.340 --> 00:39:31.070
But by any sane
definition of success,

00:39:31.070 --> 00:39:32.750
when you're laying on your
office on a pool of blood,

00:39:32.750 --> 00:39:35.420
you're not successful with the
way you're living your life,

00:39:35.420 --> 00:39:36.040
right?

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:37.890
So the idea is that
this actually is going

00:39:37.890 --> 00:39:39.490
to create--and some of you,
especially here at Google,

00:39:39.490 --> 00:39:41.281
you're young enough,
you're healthy enough,

00:39:41.281 --> 00:39:44.200
you can get by doing it,
but the reality is it's not

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:45.380
sustainable.

00:39:45.380 --> 00:39:46.990
And I think again
organizationally,

00:39:46.990 --> 00:39:48.150
people understand
that here at Google,

00:39:48.150 --> 00:39:50.060
and even your own
manager or your own team,

00:39:50.060 --> 00:39:51.310
start to make some agreements.

00:39:51.310 --> 00:39:54.190
How do we get the work done,
and how do we do it in a way

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:56.890
that people aren't
fried in the process?

00:39:56.890 --> 00:39:58.450
Because everyone's
dealing with that.

00:39:58.450 --> 00:40:00.658
And at the very least start
to have the conversation,

00:40:00.658 --> 00:40:02.380
to be open to are
there different ways

00:40:02.380 --> 00:40:03.730
we could work and communicate?

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:05.820
Are there different ways
we could keep hours?

00:40:05.820 --> 00:40:06.532
I don't know.

00:40:06.532 --> 00:40:08.240
And depending on your
role and your team,

00:40:08.240 --> 00:40:09.990
and sometimes there's
deadlines or there's

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:13.140
products or things-focused,
it's going to ebb and flow.

00:40:13.140 --> 00:40:15.040
But I think there's
a lot more discussion

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:16.415
we can have about
it, and there's

00:40:16.415 --> 00:40:19.300
a lot of science and research
backing up the importance of it

00:40:19.300 --> 00:40:22.990
on our physical well-being and
then on our productivity level.

00:40:22.990 --> 00:40:24.725
Arianna just did an
interview with Oprah

00:40:24.725 --> 00:40:27.099
on "Super Soul Sunday", and
they were both talking about,

00:40:27.099 --> 00:40:30.635
as two very, very successful
people, two things that came up

00:40:30.635 --> 00:40:32.510
in that interview I
thought were interesting.

00:40:32.510 --> 00:40:34.840
They were talking about
burnout, and Oprah

00:40:34.840 --> 00:40:38.007
was saying, if you work one
of those crazy, long, 14-hour

00:40:38.007 --> 00:40:39.590
days, you know those
last couple hours

00:40:39.590 --> 00:40:40.715
you're not very productive.

00:40:40.715 --> 00:40:43.040
It's just impossible.

00:40:43.040 --> 00:40:44.457
But the other
thing-- Arianna said

00:40:44.457 --> 00:40:46.123
one of the questions
she gets, and Oprah

00:40:46.123 --> 00:40:47.580
mentioned someone
said this to her

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:49.371
when she knew she was
going to have Arianna

00:40:49.371 --> 00:40:52.407
on-- oh, yeah, easy for you
guys to say sleep eight hours

00:40:52.407 --> 00:40:53.490
and take care of yourself.

00:40:53.490 --> 00:40:55.490
Now you're Oprah Winfrey
and Arianna Huffington.

00:40:55.490 --> 00:40:56.894
Like, how did you get there?

00:40:56.894 --> 00:40:59.060
But they both said that
actually some of the biggest

00:40:59.060 --> 00:41:00.800
regrets they had in their
lives and their careers were

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:02.790
the times they worked
too much, and they

00:41:02.790 --> 00:41:05.070
had things out of
balance and out of-- it

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:08.540
wasn't ultimately sustainable
and didn't lead them

00:41:08.540 --> 00:41:10.812
to where they got to.

00:41:10.812 --> 00:41:12.270
Now most of us
aren't at that level

00:41:12.270 --> 00:41:14.220
and probably won't
get to that level.

00:41:14.220 --> 00:41:17.240
But all of us have busy
lives and lots to manage.

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:18.760
And so in terms of
how you influence

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:21.570
the environment around
you, you communicate,

00:41:21.570 --> 00:41:23.534
you model it, and see
if you can engage.

00:41:23.534 --> 00:41:24.200
That make sense?

00:41:24.200 --> 00:41:26.670
AUDIENCE: Maybe you can to talk
a little bit about-- so you

00:41:26.670 --> 00:41:28.253
said that I think
in our culture we're

00:41:28.253 --> 00:41:30.420
very used to this idea that,
like, no pain, no gain.

00:41:30.420 --> 00:41:33.340
So unless it's you know,
things of great worth

00:41:33.340 --> 00:41:35.402
take great effort,
unless it's painful,

00:41:35.402 --> 00:41:36.860
we don't actually
get what we want.

00:41:36.860 --> 00:41:39.193
And you said that with your
third book, that you kind of

00:41:39.193 --> 00:41:41.340
had this revelation of
like, wow, this is easy.

00:41:41.340 --> 00:41:43.590
Tell us a little bit about
how you worked through that

00:41:43.590 --> 00:41:45.970
and how that could be
applicable for people like us.

00:41:45.970 --> 00:41:47.030
MIKE ROBBINS: So how
it could be easy.

00:41:47.030 --> 00:41:49.040
Yeah, I mean I first had
to confront the fact that I

00:41:49.040 --> 00:41:50.870
was really attached to
suffering and struggling.

00:41:50.870 --> 00:41:52.530
And that had been
for most of my life.

00:41:52.530 --> 00:41:54.630
And look, it's not like
I have this figured out.

00:41:54.630 --> 00:41:57.790
I mean in the process of
this, that part of my-- look,

00:41:57.790 --> 00:41:59.710
I mean one of the
things as an athlete--

00:41:59.710 --> 00:42:01.699
you know, we all have a
story about ourselves.

00:42:01.699 --> 00:42:03.740
Some parts of it are really
heroic and wonderful,

00:42:03.740 --> 00:42:04.889
some parts aren't so much.

00:42:04.889 --> 00:42:07.180
We constantly need to revisit
that story and realize A,

00:42:07.180 --> 00:42:08.014
it's not true.

00:42:08.014 --> 00:42:10.180
We keep making it up and
the more we tell the story,

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:11.570
the more real it becomes.

00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:14.270
But part of my story has
been, I'm a scrapper.

00:42:14.270 --> 00:42:15.920
I'm kind of a scrappy guy.

00:42:15.920 --> 00:42:17.624
Like I'm barely six feet tall.

00:42:17.624 --> 00:42:18.790
I was a left-handed pitcher.

00:42:18.790 --> 00:42:20.248
So this started in
baseball for me.

00:42:20.248 --> 00:42:22.020
I wasn't the most
physically talented guy,

00:42:22.020 --> 00:42:23.670
but there were very
few guys I ever

00:42:23.670 --> 00:42:25.530
played with who worked
harder than I did.

00:42:25.530 --> 00:42:27.140
And I got a lot of
positive feedback.

00:42:27.140 --> 00:42:28.540
Look at Robbins, he's
always going the extra mile.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:30.670
Look at Robbins, he's staying
after practice, way to go.

00:42:30.670 --> 00:42:32.794
And for me it was like,
OK, that's one of the ways.

00:42:32.794 --> 00:42:34.460
I wasn't blessed to
be six foot five.

00:42:34.460 --> 00:42:36.160
I couldn't throw
95 miles an hour.

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:38.380
And as I started to
get better in baseball,

00:42:38.380 --> 00:42:40.880
I realized that hard work--or
this is what I made up and was

00:42:40.880 --> 00:42:43.296
told-- Robbins, you're going
to have to just keep grinding

00:42:43.296 --> 00:42:44.280
hard.

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:44.990
OK.

00:42:44.990 --> 00:42:45.770
I could do that.

00:42:45.770 --> 00:42:46.680
Because I could control that.

00:42:46.680 --> 00:42:48.013
My effort level I could control.

00:42:48.013 --> 00:42:50.510
I couldn't always
control my talent level.

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:51.312
I got what I got.

00:42:51.312 --> 00:42:52.770
And I couldn't
control the outcome.

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:54.290
In baseball-- even if you
don't follow baseball,

00:42:54.290 --> 00:42:55.665
one of the things
about baseball,

00:42:55.665 --> 00:42:58.280
it is filled with an
enormous amount of failure.

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:01.600
It is a game-- the best
hitters in baseball

00:43:01.600 --> 00:43:04.254
get out seven out of 10 times.

00:43:04.254 --> 00:43:05.170
It's a lot of failure.

00:43:05.170 --> 00:43:06.102
I was a pitcher.

00:43:06.102 --> 00:43:07.560
And pitching, and
some of you heard

00:43:07.560 --> 00:43:09.352
me tell-- pitching is
awful in lot of ways.

00:43:09.352 --> 00:43:11.518
Because you know what happens
to a pitcher in a game

00:43:11.518 --> 00:43:13.600
when the pitcher
doesn't do well?

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:17.672
They literally stop the
game and take you out.

00:43:17.672 --> 00:43:19.880
Can you imagine if you're
having a rough day at work,

00:43:19.880 --> 00:43:22.584
you mess something up, and
literally your manager bursts

00:43:22.584 --> 00:43:24.750
in the door or pops up on
your screen and says, you.

00:43:24.750 --> 00:43:25.350
Leave.

00:43:25.350 --> 00:43:27.740
And you have to walk out
and some other person

00:43:27.740 --> 00:43:30.030
starts doing your work for you.

00:43:30.030 --> 00:43:31.920
It's pretty humiliating.

00:43:31.920 --> 00:43:33.700
So a lot of failure in baseball.

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:36.140
But I worked really
hard, worked really hard,

00:43:36.140 --> 00:43:37.480
worked really hard.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:40.330
When I got into my business--
I start my business

00:43:40.330 --> 00:43:41.950
at 26 years old.

00:43:41.950 --> 00:43:45.530
Now back in 2000-2001 when I
started my business as a coach

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:48.460
and wanting to be
an author, it was

00:43:48.460 --> 00:43:50.140
starting to be a
bigger industry.

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:52.919
But there was no social media,
there was no blog world.

00:43:52.919 --> 00:43:54.460
The only ways people
went about doing

00:43:54.460 --> 00:43:56.400
that was you had to
go through pretty

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:58.450
conventional, traditional
ways to do it.

00:43:58.450 --> 00:44:01.880
Hope to write a book, get some
notoriety, get on some TV show

00:44:01.880 --> 00:44:05.522
or whatever.

00:44:05.522 --> 00:44:07.480
And it was like, I'm
going to work really hard,

00:44:07.480 --> 00:44:08.610
I'm going to hustle.

00:44:08.610 --> 00:44:10.900
So all of that to say,
that's kind of in my DNA.

00:44:10.900 --> 00:44:12.200
And there are some
positive sides to that.

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:14.050
It's not like I want
to throw that all out.

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:17.120
But I think the process
for me has been looking at,

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:18.770
who the people
that I know-- this

00:44:18.770 --> 00:44:20.130
is a big thing, modeling
other people-- who

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:22.810
are the people that I know that
look like they're able to make

00:44:22.810 --> 00:44:26.250
things happen with a
minimal amount of effort.

00:44:26.250 --> 00:44:29.420
Because people like that, it's
like there's pixie dust on them

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:31.490
somehow and everything
they touch turns to gold?

00:44:31.490 --> 00:44:33.460
That is actually a
conscious, deliberate thing,

00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:36.016
whether they're fully aware
of what they're doing or not.

00:44:36.016 --> 00:44:37.390
And I started to
realize, I think

00:44:37.390 --> 00:44:39.820
I want a little more of that.

00:44:39.820 --> 00:44:42.490
And I'll share this with you,
just because in the context--

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:43.406
I didn't write a book.

00:44:43.406 --> 00:44:45.327
I wrote my first book
'07, my second book '09.

00:44:45.327 --> 00:44:47.660
"Focus on the Good Stuff"
came out in '07, "Be Yourself"

00:44:47.660 --> 00:44:48.710
came out on '09.

00:44:48.710 --> 00:44:50.730
And we had two babies
and I wrote two books

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:52.830
in the span of three years.

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:55.270
I didn't sleep much,
I wasn't very healthy,

00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:56.622
I wasn't very happy.

00:44:56.622 --> 00:44:59.080
The end of 2009-- and I write
a lot about this in the book.

00:44:59.080 --> 00:45:00.452
Michelle and I both.

00:45:00.452 --> 00:45:02.660
I literally looked at her
one day and said, hey babe,

00:45:02.660 --> 00:45:04.250
I got an idea.

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:07.220
How about we stop focusing
so much of our attention

00:45:07.220 --> 00:45:09.360
on trying to look
happy and successful

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:11.206
and actually be
happy and successful?

00:45:11.206 --> 00:45:12.580
Because I bet if
we actually are,

00:45:12.580 --> 00:45:14.966
we'll probably look like it too.

00:45:14.966 --> 00:45:16.340
Because here we
were in this life

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:18.463
that we thought we wanted,
with kids and I was doing work,

00:45:18.463 --> 00:45:19.320
it was all great.

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:22.230
But underneath we
were stressed out.

00:45:22.230 --> 00:45:23.150
We were tired.

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:24.650
We were in debt.

00:45:24.650 --> 00:45:27.480
Things weren't how
we wanted them to be.

00:45:27.480 --> 00:45:30.240
So when I started to think
about writing the next book,

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:31.900
I didn't even know what it was
going to be about, but I said,

00:45:31.900 --> 00:45:32.960
I don't know what it's
going to be about,

00:45:32.960 --> 00:45:35.251
but it's going to be a much
more pleasurable experience

00:45:35.251 --> 00:45:36.070
to write.

00:45:36.070 --> 00:45:37.570
And it took me many
years to finally

00:45:37.570 --> 00:45:39.821
get ready to be in a place
where I could do that.

00:45:39.821 --> 00:45:41.070
Lots of ups and downs in life.

00:45:41.070 --> 00:45:42.528
But things started
to go well and I

00:45:42.528 --> 00:45:44.860
started to feel like,
OK, I can do this.

00:45:44.860 --> 00:45:48.526
When I finally sat down to
write this book last summer--

00:45:48.526 --> 00:45:50.880
I have a tendency sometimes
to procrastinate on things.

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:52.490
And of you ever do that?

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:54.220
Big deadline.

00:45:54.220 --> 00:45:57.610
But I finally committed,
I'm going to do this.

00:45:57.610 --> 00:45:59.285
I wrote the book in seven weeks.

00:45:59.285 --> 00:46:03.170
Now I kind of had to
because it was due, right?

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:06.780
But it was actually 17
days of writing, that's it.

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:08.552
I use Dragon speech
recognition software

00:46:08.552 --> 00:46:10.760
because I'm such more of a
talker than I am a writer.

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:12.385
But you know what,
for the longest time

00:46:12.385 --> 00:46:13.570
I thought that was cheating.

00:46:13.570 --> 00:46:15.445
Can't really talk a
book, you gotta write it.

00:46:15.445 --> 00:46:16.730
It's got to be hard, right?

00:46:16.730 --> 00:46:18.313
And I share that
with you because what

00:46:18.313 --> 00:46:22.950
happened for me is I started to
realize, it's OK if it's easy.

00:46:22.950 --> 00:46:25.257
I don't have to
apologize for that.

00:46:25.257 --> 00:46:27.590
So for a lot of us-- look,
nothing wrong with hard work.

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:29.060
I'm not saying
that's a bad thing.

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:31.240
But this idea that we have
to suffer and struggle

00:46:31.240 --> 00:46:33.980
and things have to be
hard-- I'm now to the point

00:46:33.980 --> 00:46:37.420
where my new practice in
life is, if it's too hard,

00:46:37.420 --> 00:46:39.300
I'm actually going
to rethink about

00:46:39.300 --> 00:46:40.554
do I really want to do it.

00:46:40.554 --> 00:46:42.220
Or as a friend of
mine used to say to me

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:45.080
all the time, just because you
can doesn't mean you should.

00:46:48.080 --> 00:46:48.580
Yeah.

00:46:48.580 --> 00:46:50.600
AUDIENCE: We all have
had successes in life.

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:54.350
But some of my best
successes felt really easy,

00:46:54.350 --> 00:46:57.090
and when people would actually
congratulate me, I would like,

00:46:57.090 --> 00:47:02.830
just-- I wouldn't accept--
internally I wouldn't accept it

00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:05.664
and I'd be like,
oh, that was easy.

00:47:05.664 --> 00:47:07.080
So how do we get
over, how do we--

00:47:07.080 --> 00:47:08.730
MIKE ROBBINS: I think
we take a lot of things

00:47:08.730 --> 00:47:10.630
for granted about ourselves,
some of our strengths, some

00:47:10.630 --> 00:47:12.780
of our gifts and things
that do come easy.

00:47:12.780 --> 00:47:15.730
And I would really challenge
all of us not to do that,

00:47:15.730 --> 00:47:17.940
to really be grateful for
the things that come easy.

00:47:17.940 --> 00:47:19.648
And then ask ourselves
a deeper question,

00:47:19.648 --> 00:47:22.510
less about the outcome and
more about the experience.

00:47:22.510 --> 00:47:24.300
Is this what I want?

00:47:24.300 --> 00:47:26.450
And if it does come
easy, be grateful

00:47:26.450 --> 00:47:28.490
and feel blessed that it does.

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:30.450
Say thank you to
whatever you believe in.

00:47:30.450 --> 00:47:31.130
Thank you.

00:47:31.130 --> 00:47:32.340
This is easy for me.

00:47:32.340 --> 00:47:34.090
And be mindful of the fact that
it's not easy for everybody.

00:47:34.090 --> 00:47:36.423
So without bragging about it
or being arrogant about it,

00:47:36.423 --> 00:47:37.840
it's like, wow.

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:38.780
Something for me.

00:47:38.780 --> 00:47:39.470
I speak.

00:47:39.470 --> 00:47:40.990
I've worked at this.

00:47:40.990 --> 00:47:43.550
But this actually is
really easy for me.

00:47:43.550 --> 00:47:46.940
And it's taken me awhile--
wow, wow, you're good at that.

00:47:46.940 --> 00:47:49.440
I've done it a lot,
that makes it easier.

00:47:49.440 --> 00:47:52.380
But I was born with a certain
gift, that this is what I do.

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:53.720
This is how I express myself.

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:55.361
So that's OK.

00:47:55.361 --> 00:47:57.360
Then we focus on the
things that don't, and then

00:47:57.360 --> 00:47:58.901
we spend a lot of
time thinking, I've

00:47:58.901 --> 00:48:00.530
got to improve those things.

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:01.680
So it's big one.

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:03.096
Now let me say
this, because we've

00:48:03.096 --> 00:48:04.720
got to wrap this
up, just time-wise.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:06.290
I'll stick around for
those of you who are here

00:48:06.290 --> 00:48:08.250
if you've got questions,
you want to chat with me.

00:48:08.250 --> 00:48:09.010
Happy to talk to you.

00:48:09.010 --> 00:48:10.800
Those of you on the video
or on the live stream,

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:12.802
we can stay in touch
just through my website,

00:48:12.802 --> 00:48:13.510
mike-robbins.com.

00:48:13.510 --> 00:48:16.167
But I want to close
with one last story just

00:48:16.167 --> 00:48:17.750
to kind of bring
this all full circle,

00:48:17.750 --> 00:48:20.395
because one of the key
things for us in all of this

00:48:20.395 --> 00:48:22.530
is perspective.

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:25.945
I wrote this book primarily
about perspective,

00:48:25.945 --> 00:48:27.070
perspective in my own life.

00:48:27.070 --> 00:48:29.736
And one of the things-- and many
of you sitting here in the room

00:48:29.736 --> 00:48:32.072
have the book itself-- but
I write a bit in the book

00:48:32.072 --> 00:48:33.530
about an experience
that was really

00:48:33.530 --> 00:48:35.900
poignant in my life over
these last few years,

00:48:35.900 --> 00:48:38.160
and that's the death of my mom.

00:48:38.160 --> 00:48:40.570
So my mom died in 2011.

00:48:40.570 --> 00:48:42.640
And what was interesting
about that experience--

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:44.060
and any of you who've
lost people close

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:45.476
have probably had
this experience.

00:48:45.476 --> 00:48:47.820
Really painful,
really difficult,

00:48:47.820 --> 00:48:52.130
but incredibly growth-inducing,
and actually quite beautiful,

00:48:52.130 --> 00:48:54.440
even in the midst of
the pain and sadness.

00:48:54.440 --> 00:48:57.420
And one of the most poignant
moments for me-- my mom got

00:48:57.420 --> 00:49:01.120
diagnosed with lung cancer in
March and she died in June,

00:49:01.120 --> 00:49:03.370
so it happened pretty quickly.

00:49:03.370 --> 00:49:05.380
And in some ways that
was actually a blessing.

00:49:05.380 --> 00:49:06.770
But she knew it was
going to happen,

00:49:06.770 --> 00:49:07.894
and she really surrendered.

00:49:07.894 --> 00:49:08.780
And my mom was tough.

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:11.114
My mom was like, single
mom, raised two kids,

00:49:11.114 --> 00:49:12.030
we grew up in Oakland.

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:14.446
You couldn't mess with my mom,
she was that kind of woman.

00:49:14.446 --> 00:49:16.930
But towards the end she
really started to surrender

00:49:16.930 --> 00:49:17.840
and she really
started to open up.

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:19.332
And we had beautiful
conversations,

00:49:19.332 --> 00:49:20.790
and there was
amazing healings that

00:49:20.790 --> 00:49:22.970
happened in our
relationship and our family.

00:49:22.970 --> 00:49:25.860
It was just-- now none of
us wanted it to happen,

00:49:25.860 --> 00:49:27.860
so it was really sad and
painful on many levels.

00:49:27.860 --> 00:49:29.485
But it was such a
beautiful experience.

00:49:29.485 --> 00:49:32.830
And there was a morning I got
up--it was probably about,

00:49:32.830 --> 00:49:34.510
I don't know, a
month and a half,

00:49:34.510 --> 00:49:37.674
two months before she died-- but
we knew, OK, this is serious,

00:49:37.674 --> 00:49:38.840
we know where this is going.

00:49:38.840 --> 00:49:40.970
There wasn't thought of--
it happened even quicker

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:41.636
than we thought.

00:49:41.636 --> 00:49:43.370
So I'm on this run.

00:49:43.370 --> 00:49:45.920
I had spent the night at my
childhood home in Oakland.

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:46.960
A lot of emotion.

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:48.750
I get up that morning,
I go for a run.

00:49:48.750 --> 00:49:50.834
And I'm thinking in
my mind about my mom

00:49:50.834 --> 00:49:52.750
and the whole situation
and I think to myself,

00:49:52.750 --> 00:49:55.840
I wonder what it's like
for my mother right now,

00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:57.257
knowing that she's going to die?

00:49:57.257 --> 00:49:58.340
What would that feel like?

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:00.270
What would that be like?

00:50:00.270 --> 00:50:02.810
And as I'm having that thought
I literally stopped running

00:50:02.810 --> 00:50:06.220
and I went, wait a minute.

00:50:06.220 --> 00:50:08.560
I know I'm going to die.

00:50:08.560 --> 00:50:11.660
I just don't know when.

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:13.526
But I don't live like that.

00:50:13.526 --> 00:50:14.900
I live with this
erroneous notion

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:16.440
of certainty, like I know
what's going to happen,

00:50:16.440 --> 00:50:17.960
like I know my girls
are going to grow up,

00:50:17.960 --> 00:50:19.330
and my wife, and this,
and I'm going to do this,

00:50:19.330 --> 00:50:20.610
and I have all these
plans and these goals.

00:50:20.610 --> 00:50:22.609
And those things are all
really important to me.

00:50:22.609 --> 00:50:25.400
But I stopped and
went, wait a second.

00:50:25.400 --> 00:50:27.960
What if I started to live
my life in a healthy way,

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:31.820
in an empowering way, from
that perspective of knowing

00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:33.350
I'm not going to
be here forever.

00:50:33.350 --> 00:50:34.570
None of us are going
to be here forever.

00:50:34.570 --> 00:50:35.880
Everybody we're
in a relationship

00:50:35.880 --> 00:50:37.796
with, everything we're
doing, everything here,

00:50:37.796 --> 00:50:41.410
as extraordinary as this place
is, Google, it's temporary.

00:50:41.410 --> 00:50:43.480
It's not permanent.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:46.389
And if we can remember that,
and hold life-- hold our goals

00:50:46.389 --> 00:50:47.930
and our dreams and
our relationships,

00:50:47.930 --> 00:50:50.270
and even the things that
are most important to us--

00:50:50.270 --> 00:50:53.070
with an open hand, with
a sense of intention

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:55.935
but not grasping so hard to
it, that all of a sudden,

00:50:55.935 --> 00:50:58.560
a lot of the stuff that we worry
about and that we stress about

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:00.310
and that we get
upset about, it just

00:51:00.310 --> 00:51:02.670
doesn't matter in
the face of that.

00:51:02.670 --> 00:51:04.360
And that's one of
the many blessings

00:51:04.360 --> 00:51:07.400
that I got from that
very painful experience.

00:51:07.400 --> 00:51:10.330
And if we start to live our
lives from that perspective,

00:51:10.330 --> 00:51:11.860
and look around
and realize we're

00:51:11.860 --> 00:51:14.530
the common denominator in
every relationship we have

00:51:14.530 --> 00:51:16.380
and everything we do.

00:51:16.380 --> 00:51:17.880
And when we can
shift internally,

00:51:17.880 --> 00:51:21.020
be more kind and compassionate
and loving towards ourselves,

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:24.250
keep things in perspective,
then everyone and everything

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:28.780
we interact with
literally changes.

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:30.000
Thanks for coming.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:33.650
[APPLAUSE]

